[1mBUGS[0m
   [1mReporting Bugs[0m
       Email bug reports to the bug-reporting address  ‚ü®bug-grep@gnu.org‚ü©.   An  email  archive
       ‚ü®https://lists.gnu.org/mailman/listinfo/bug-grep‚ü©       and      a      bug      tracker
       ‚ü®https://debbugs.gnu.org/cgi/pkgreport.cgi?package=grep‚ü© are available.

   [1mKnown Bugs[0m
       Large repetition counts in the [1m{[4m[22mn[24m[1m,[4m[22mm[24m[1m} [22mconstruct may cause [1mgrep [22mto use lots of memory.  In
       addition,  certain other obscure regular expressions require exponential time and space,
       and may cause [1mgrep [22mto run out of memory.

       Back-references are very slow, and may require exponential time.

[1mEXAMPLE[0m
       The following example outputs the location and contents of any line containing  ‚Äúf‚Äù  and
       ending  in  ‚Äú.c‚Äù,  within all files in the current directory whose names contain ‚Äúg‚Äù and
       end in ‚Äú.h‚Äù.  The [1m-n [22moption outputs line numbers, the [1m-- [22margument treats  expansions  of
       ‚Äú*g*.h‚Äù starting with ‚Äú-‚Äù as file names not options, and the empty file /dev/null causes
       file names to be output even if only one file name happens to be of the form ‚Äú*g*.h‚Äù.

         $ [1mgrep [22m-n -- 'f.*\.c$' *g*.h /dev/null
         argmatch.h:1:/* definitions and prototypes for argmatch.c

       The only line that matches is line 1 of argmatch.h.  Note that  the  regular  expression
       syntax used in the pattern differs from the globbing syntax that the shell uses to match
       file names.

